<br>
Ya, I geuss. But there is nothing at all great in strictly speaking making a currency.<br>
<br>
I'll make one now:<br>
<br>
1) I'll start two corporations. Hoefensfill A and Hoefensfill B.<br>
2) I'll also be the central bank and make 10,000 Hoefensbills.<br>
3) Hoefensfill A and B each get 2,000 hoefensbills. <br>
4) Hoefensfill A will rip pieces of paper which Hoefensfill B needs. Hoefensfill B will drop paper on the floor. A likes to watch B drop things on the floor.<br>
5) B buys paper from A, which then pays to watch it be dropped on the floor.<br>
<br>
There I created a theoretically real currency. Should I be proud? <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
Obviously I'm not saying Hannover's system is like Hoefensbills but my point is both, as far as theory goes, everything goes. What really matters in terms of giving anything new to a nation, is the value in practice and not just in theory. In any pratical terms you are working towards a proper economy but as of yet its just not an economy for the overwhelming majority of people.<br>
